[[Image:Clach Biorach.JPG|thumb|A distance photograph of ''Clach Biorach'' taken in July 2006.]]
[[File:"Clach Biorach" (The Pointed Stone), Ardmore - geograph.org.uk - 915406.jpg|thumb|"Clach Biorach" (The Pointed Stone), Ardmore]]
The '''Clach Biorach''' (in [[English language|English]], "Sharp Stone") is a three-metre [[Standing Stone]] located {{convert|1/4|mile|km}} north-west of the village of [[Edderton]] in [[Easter Ross]]. It dates to the [[Bronze Age]], but two Pictish-style symbols were later engraved on the north side, making it a Class I [[Pictish stones|Pictish symbol stone]]. The symbols are a 1) [[Double disc (Pictish symbol)|double-disc]] with a [[Z-rod (Pictish symbol)|z-rod]], and 2) a [[Salmon (Pictish symbol)|salmon]] above.

==References==
* MacNamara, Ellen, ''The Pictish Stones of Easter Ross'', (Tain, 2003)
* Scott, Douglas, ''The Stones of the Pictish Peninsulas'', (Hilton Trust, 2004)

