{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Hans Holbein the Younger - Margaret Roper (Metropolitan Museum of Art).JPG | title=Portrait Miniature of Margaret Roper | artist=[[Hans Holbein the Younger]] | year=c. 1535–36 | type=Bodycolour on [[vellum]] mounted on card | diameter_metric=4.5 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | museum=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] | city=New York }}
'''''Portrait Miniature of Margaret Roper''''' is a painting by the German artist and printmaker [[Hans Holbein the Younger]] created between 1535–36, and today held in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref name="met1">"[http://www.metmuseum.org/works_of_art/collection_database/european_paintings/margaret_more_1505_1544_wife_of_william_roper_hans_holbein_the_younger/objectview.aspx?collID=11&OID=110001105 Margaret More]". [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]. Retrieved on 17 May 2009.</ref> [[Margaret Roper]] (1505–44) was the eldest child of [[Thomas More|Sir Thomas More]] and wife of the English biographer [[William Roper (biographer)|William Roper]]. It is the second and less well known of two portraits of Roper painted by Holbein. The first, ''Portrait of an English Woman'', is generally believed to show Roper but may depict another unknown lady of the English court. The New York work was painted during the artist's second visit to London, likely in the mid-1530s.<ref name="G92">Goldberg, 92</ref><ref>"[https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/pd/h/hans_holbein_the_younger,_port.aspx Hans Holbein the Younger, Portrait of an English Woman, a drawing]". [[British Museum]], Retrieved 11 April 2010</ref>
It is believed that the work was created shortly after her father's beheading at the hands of King [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] in 1535.<ref name="mm12">"[http://12.151.120.44/toah/ho/08/euwb/ho_50.69.2.htm Margaret More (1505–1544), Wife of William Roper, 1535–36]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}". Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History, Metropolitan Museum of Art. Retrieved on 17 May 2009.</ref> With a diameter of just {{convert|1+3/4|in|cm}}, the work was one of over a hundred [[Portrait miniature|miniature]]s and portraits painted by Holbein while in England. This work is one of a pair of [[pendant]]s; the second depicts the sitter's husband.
Roper is depicted in three-quarters view with a narrow face and wearing extravagant clothes that reflect her social position. She is wearing a [[gable hood]] with pinned up red/orange embroidered lappets (facing the viewer) and a long black veil (with one side pinned up). Her black gown is lined with a broad band of fur. She holds a green book in her hands which are decorated by gold rings. A horizontal gold inscription reads "Ao ÆTATIS XXX".<ref name="met1" /> The work was donated to the Metropolitan Museum by the Rogers Fund in 1950.
