'''''Principia philosophiae cartesianae''''' ('''''PPC'''''; "The Principles of Cartesian Philosophy") or '''''Renati Descartes principia philosophiae, more geometrico demonstrata''''' ("The Principles of René Descartes' Philosophy, Demonstrated in Geometrical Order") is a philosophical work of [[Baruch Spinoza]] published in [[Amsterdam]] in 1663. In the preface to this work, Ludovic Meyer explains that it is a reconstruction of [[René Descartes]]' ''[[Principles of Philosophy]] ''in the Euclidean or "geometric" fashion''[[Principles of Philosophy|.]] ''In the appendix, a series of non-geometric prose passages entitled ''Metaphysical Thoughts'' [''Cogitata Metaphisica''], Spinoza explicates [[Cartesian materialism|Descartes' views]] on traditional metaphysical topics (including [[essence]], [[existence]], [[idea]], [[potential]], [[Metaphysical necessity|necessity]], [[contingency (philosophy)|contingency]], [[duration (philosophy)|duration]], and [[time]]) while furtively interpolating some of his own.

{{Baruch Spinoza}}

[[Category:Works by Baruch Spinoza]]
